Esat Musliu’s Vitet e pritjes/Years of Waiting (1990): Emigration and women -- tTowards the future -- tBibliography -- tFilmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlbanian cinema truly represents a terra incognita for most of the world. Decidedly Europe’s most isolated country during the Cold War era, communist Albania had already been cut off from the West for centuries as a one of the western-most outposts of the Ottoman empire. Nonetheless, and unknown to most of the world, communist Albania had a vibrant cinema tradition. Although bound by official orthodoxy, the films of the state-run Kinostudio enterprise were surprisingly innovative and, at times, daringly subversive. This book opens with examinations of moving images in Albania from the Ottoman period, through those captured under independence and the Fascist occupation. It subsequently foregrounds transformations in Kinostudio, from the early optimism of socialist realism through the brooding social angst of the 1980s, which constitute a bridge to the socioeconomic concerns of Albanian films of the postcommunist period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aFilm Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 4aPolitics and Government. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  aCinema, Albania, communism, post-communism, transnationalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048529339?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048529339423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048529339/original  a978-3-11-102374-8  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL